JollyCV
-------
JollyCV is an emulator for the ColecoVision.

JollyCV is the first emulator written specifically for The Jolly Good API. It
is focused on the educational aspects of emulation. The comments in the source
code are verbose, yet easy to follow. The ColecoVision is the perfect console
to use for educational purposes, because it is very simple and uses generic,
off-the-shelf chips with widely available documentation and datasheets.

Compiling
---------
Make sure you have The Jolly Good API's header files installed. If you did
not install them, you will be required to include their path in CFLAGS.

Linux:
  make

macOS:
  make

BSD:
  gmake

Windows (MSYS2):
  make

The build will be output to "jollycv/". This directory may be used as is
locally by copying it to your local "cores" directory, or may be installed
system-wide using the "install" target specified in the Makefile.

Input Devices
-------------
JollyCV currently supports the following input devices:

ColecoVision Paddle

Settings
--------
palette = 0 
0 = TeaTime, 1 = SYoung

rsqual = 3
N = Resampler Quality (0-10)

region = 0
0 = NTSC, 1 = PAL

Known Problems
--------------
This emulator is still very new, so it is not perfect. Compatibility is
extremely high, but the following software is presently not usable:

Lord of the Dungeon (USA) (Beta) - Likely needs SRAM support implemented

Other software may require input devices that are not currently emulated.

Porting
-------
JollyCV was written in standards compliant ISO C99 and should be extremely
portable. Though it was written for The Jolly Good API, it was done in a
manner that allows it to be used easily in multi-emulator frameworks or
standalone binaries for many potential platforms. If a new port is created,
a clear indication that it is not an official port should be made, either
by changing the name of the project or appending to it. Please be an
honest person and respect the licenses that apply to the software.

